==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*xebja-'', from Indo-European ''*kap-'' ‘take, seize’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[heva]], Old Saxon [[hebbian]] (Dutch [[heffen]]), Old High German [[heffen]] (German [[heben]]), Old Norse [[hefja]] (Swedish [[häva]]), Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐍆𐌾𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[capere]], Old Irish [[cacht]] (Welsh [[caeth]] ‘slave’, Breton [[keaz]] ‘poor’), Albanian [[kap]] ‘grip’, Slavic ''*xopītī-'' (Old Church Slavonic {{RUchar|[[хапѭште]]}}, Russian [[хапать]]), Baltic ''*kap-'' (Lithuanian [[kapteleti|kàpteleti]], Latvian [[kampt|kàmpt]] ‘bite’).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈheb:an/}}

===Verb===
'''hebban''' (class VI strong)
# to [[lift]], to [[raise]] up
#:''ic hond and rond hebban mihte'': I could lift hand and shield.  (''Beowulf'')

